I am carving up one last batch of herb strippers before the holidays! If you don’t know what an herb stripper is, check out the highlight reel under my bio to see one in action. 

I like this simple scalloped version. My clay was pretty dry, which was how I wanted it. I knew my @diamondcoretools fluting tool would have no problem cutting through the dryer clay and it is easier to use this particular little rasp when the clay is stiffer, otherwise the shavings could gum up the rasp. A round pottery sponge cut into half and quarters was super helpful smoothing out the grooves and defining the scalloped edge along the upper rim. 

It’s officially December 1st and the holidays are right around the corner! 😱

Tool used: @diamondcoretools X2 12 mm U Fluting Tool + Surform 10” round blade

Come carve an herb stripper with me! 
(If you don’t know what an herb stripper is, check out my highlight reel to see one in action!)

This is the last big push for makers to create their pieces before the holidays. It’s a busy time and can be a little stressful. Sometimes when I am feeling a bit overwhelmed I do my best to clear my mind and start carving without much of a plan. It forces me to focus and makes me let go of everything else. Totally clears my head - at least for a short period of time! I drew a few guidelines and some vertical dividing lines but otherwise I had no idea what I was going to carve until I picked up a tool and buried the blade in the clay. Such a great feeling!!

Self care is so important. What are you doing to keep yourself centered during this busy time?

Tool used: @diamondcoretools P11 Curved Wide V Tip 12 mm Carving Tool

Carving an ornament 🎄 
Don’t pay attention to the messy/uneven top - it will get trimmed a little and be covered by an ornament cap! 😉
This ornament came out a little on the thin side. I couldn’t carve deeply into it so I decided to try thin shallow cuts, which are way harder than they look. I’m used to carving straight, evenly spaced lines but throwing curves into the mix was a little more difficult! It was still fun though 😁

I’m still hoping to have one more sale before the holidays - before the postal cutoff dates. I can’t promise, but I will try my best. Keep an eye on my feed and stories to see shop update announcements or head over to my IG bio and subscribe to my email list to get announcements sent right to your inbox!

Last minute shop update tomorrow evening, Thursday, December 15th, 7:00pm Central Standard Time. 

Apologies for the late notice but I wanted to be sure everything made it through the firing before committing to a shop update. I will have 22 herb strippers and a handful of ornaments available as well as a few other pieces. Happy New Year!! 
Today was my first studio day of 2023. I started working on a new idea that has been knocking around in my brain for months. I wanted to take the concept of my herb stripper and enlarge it into a salad bowl that can strip kale from its stem along with any other greens that need to be stripped to create a wonderful salad in one big bowl. So this is my test bowl to see how the large holes work with kale. I’m not sure they’re big enough but we shall see 😉

The carving was completely spontaneous. I drew out the grid but didn’t know what pattern I wanted to carve. I picked up my trusty @diamondcoretools P11 blade and just started carving and a pattern emerged. 

I love my job!!

A few new carved designs on herb strippers for 2023. What do you think? Do you have a favorite? Leaves? Flowers? Or funky abstract succulents?

Stay tuned to see the finished product next week. These have been bisque fired and the color will change once they’re glazed. The blue will become a deep navy blue and the black will become a little more intense 🤩

Come strip some cilantro with me! I love this little gadget. It gets used all the time in my kitchen for so many different herbs. Cilantro is one of my favorites!

And for anyone who thinks I am wasting the best part of the plant by throwing out the stems, I included a little clip of what I do with the stems (and the cilantro root if you are able to grow your own or buy them with the root still attached). Crush them into a paste with loads of garlic, shallots, fresh chilies, lime juice, salt and pepper and anything else you like. I smear this mixture onto chicken before I grill it but you can use it in so many ways! In the video I only included a few ingredients as a last minute, quick demo but there are many things you can add to the cilantro stems to make a concoction bursting with flavor!! 

I love how this new carving style turned out. It’s one of my favorites and it’s a bummer that this one has a little crack in it but that’s ok - it just means I get to keep it and I promise to make more 😉

I made a casting/drain table today. I don’t have the space for a full size casting table in my studio but this will work great. I can store it anywhere up high or on its side and when I need it I can put it on the table or any other stable surface in my studio. After filling my molds with slip and letting them sit for the right amount of time, I will dump the remainder of the slip into a sealable container and then set the molds upside down, at an angle on the dowel rods in this box to finish draining. 

I bought the plastic box at the hardware store along with the dowels and rubber O-rings. I measured out where I wanted the holes and cut those out with a spade/paddle drill bit. I cut the dowel rods in half, inserted them into the holes and held them in place with an O ring on either side of the dowel rod so they can’t slip out - and voila! 

Now I have even more space to make lots and lots of herb strippers!!

Here is how I polish the bottoms of my mugs. I start with a 120 grit grinding disc from @diamondcoretools to be sure the mug is level and to sand off any little imperfections before moving on to a 240 grit grinding disc. Then I put my @giffingrip mini on the wheel, flip my mug over and use @diamondcoretools sanding pads in 400, 800, 1500 and 3500 grit to make the bottom silky smooth. A plastic box with one side cut out and my trusty snoopy towel helps to keep the water from splattering all over me and the studio!

⚠️ Always use plenty of water while sanding the bottoms of your pots to make sure you don’t create harmful dust in your studio!!⚠️

Herb strippers are almost ready!! Stay tuned for a shop update announcement! In the meantime, this is how I polish a stripper’s bottom 🤭

Because these are an irregular shape, I can’t polish them upside down - the same way I polish mug butts. I start out with the 120 grit grinding disc from @diamondcoretools but then I skip straight to the 400 grit and then 800 grit sanding pad. I dip them in water and the wet sanding pad sticks to the grinding disc below it just long enough for me to polish the bottoms real quick. 

Fair warning - this method is risky! Be very careful if you try to do this. The sanding pad could slip and if you’re applying too much pressure you will crash your pot right into the spinning sanding disc below!

This donut of clay has been sitting in my damp box for about 6 months. I wanted to try throwing a donut but then I didn’t have any great ideas of what to do with it. Today I decided to just go for it, carve a pattern into it and make a little vase out of it! I had to speed it up just a little (x2) to fit in the part where I totally screwed up carving the pattern 😆. I didn’t sketch out much of the pattern as a guide since I’ve carved this one several times before, but carving it around a curve like this was different. Oh well, I carved over my mistake, sponged it a little and I hope that the glaze will cover enough so it’s not so noticeable. This little donut experiment is just for me so it’s ok if it’s not perfect 😉 

I was inspired to try out donut vases watching @ceramicsbyanne 

Tool used: @diamondcoretools P17 Straight U Tip 3 mm Carving Tool

I’m using the @diamondcoretools P17 Straight U Tip 3 mm Carving Tool for most of the carving and during the last part of the video I used the L3 Diamond Sgraffito Stylus Tool to give some texture to the vine.

I’ve been curious about the effects of acupressure on the body so when the opportunity came up to test out this acupressure mat by @pranamat I quickly agreed. The acupressure mat is supposed to relieve tension, reduce aches and pains and increase blood flow along with several other benefits they list on their site. I received my Pranamat ECO a couple of weeks ago and I am impressed with the quality of the 3 piece set. To be honest I’m still in the middle of testing the use of this mat daily, so I will have to give a full review in a few weeks, but so far it’s been great - I do see a bit of improvement in my overall body stress and tension. 

As a potter I’m on my feet a lot or sitting bent over the potter’s wheel, so I was looking for something to relieve my overall body tension. The Pranamat ECO is very cool. It does take some getting used to, as the little lotus flowers that are all over the mat are hard and prickly at first, but when you lay on it with your body weight distributed across the mat, they feel really good. I started laying on the mat for 5 min at a time and increased little by little to 20 minutes at a time. I have even started a practice of standing on the smaller mat for short periods of time while I work in the studio. It’s not easy to do, but it makes my feet feel pretty good afterward. 

If you’ve been curious about acupressure to relieve stress and tension, check out the @pranamat ECO and use the code JULIETTEDAVIN to receive up to 30% off during their summer sale that started today! 🙌🏻

Thank you to @pranamat for sending me this acupressure set to test out and review.

I decided to try standing on my @pranamat ECO for short periods of time while working in my studio. This was quite a challenge as the little lotus flower spikes take some getting used to, but then I found that it felt pretty awesome. I started out using socks to buffer the little spikes and I used it on a padded, carpeted surface and then moved to using it barefoot on the hard floor of my studio. The little spikes definitely get my attention but I’ve gotten used to them.
